<span class="date"><a href="mailto:aracnakat@rpgplanet.com">Aracnakat</a> | 11/29/2000 - 1:07<br></span><br>
<span class="news"><font color="9999cc"></span></font>
<span class="news"><a href="http://www.voodooextreme.com">VoodooExtreme</a> caught up with Brian Hook - that announced yesterday he was leaving Verant Interactive - and asked him some quesitions about his future plans. Here's a rip from the interview:<br><br>

<ul>"<b>VoodooExtreme</b>: Why did you leave Verant?<br><br>

<b>Brian Hook</b>: First, let me state up front that this was a completely amicable departure.  Verant was very good to me.  Smed [John Smedley, Verant/SOE Executive VP] and I have a good rapport, and he’s a genuinely good guy that I like a lot.<br><br>

But to answer your question, I was just getting uncomfortable with the very corporate environment there.  You have to understand my background  I left 3Dfx when it had less than 50 employees; when I worked for Silicon Graphics I was just a contractor, so I never had to deal with “big company” issues; and at id there were about a dozen employees.  So I come from a very small company mentality.  When I went to Verant it felt absolutely huge  I think there were about 70 or so employees, but I don’t quite remember  but after the acquisition by Sony it got even huger.  All of a sudden I was working for this gigantic company based out of Japan instead of a relatively small game developer, and that just wasn’t as enjoyable for me.  This isn’t a slam on Sony, it’s just that I’m a lot more comfortable working with a small group of people without a lot of corporate “stuff” to deal with."</ul>

Read the full <a href="http://www.voodooextreme.com/games/interviews/hook/">interview here.</span></p>
